{{History of Japan |image=Shoso-in.jpg |caption=[[Shōsōin]]}}

{{nihongo|'''''Einin'''''|永仁}} was a {{nihongo|[[Japanese era name]]|年号,|''nengō'',|lit. "year name"}} after ''[[Shōō (Kamakura period)|Shōō]]'' and before ''[[Shōan]].''  This period spanned the years from August 1293 through April 1299.<ref>Nussbaum, Louis-Frédéric. (2005). "''Einin''" in {{Google books|p2QnPijAEmEC|''Japan Encyclopedia'', p. 171|page=171}}; n.b., Louis-Frédéric is pseudonym of Louis-Frédéric Nussbaum, ''see'' [https://archive.is/20120524174828/http://dispatch.opac.ddb.de/DB=4.1/PPN?PPN=128842709 Deutsche Nationalbibliothek Authority File].</ref> The reigning emperors were {{nihongo|[[Emperor Fushimi|Fushimi]]''-tennō''|伏見天皇}} and {{nihongo|[[Emperor Go-Fushimi|Go-Fushimi]]''-tennō''|後伏見天皇}}.<ref>Titsingh, Isaac. (1834). ''Annales des empereurs du japon'', p. 269-274; Varley, H. Paul. (1980). ''Jinnō Shōtōki.'' pp. 237-238.</ref>

==Change of era==
* '''1293''' {{nihongo|''Einin gannen''|永仁元年}}: The new era name was created to mark an event or a number of events. The previous era ended and a new one commenced in ''Shō'ō'' 6.

==Events of the ''Einen'' era==
* '''1298''' (''Einin 6, 7th month''): In the 11th year of Fushimi''-tennō'' 's reign (伏見天皇11年), the emperor abdicated; and the succession (''senso'') was received by his son.<ref>Titsingh, p. 274; Varley, p. 44; a distinct act of ''senso'' is unrecognized prior to [[Emperor Tenji]]; and all sovereigns except [[Empress Jitō|Jitō]], [[Emperor Yōzei|Yōzei]], [[Emperor Go-Toba|Go-Toba]], and [[Emperor Fushimi|Fushimi]] have ''senso'' and ''sokui'' in the same year until the reign of [[Emperor Go-Murakami]].</ref>
* '''1299''' (''Einin 7''): Emperor Go-Fushimi is said to have acceded to the throne (''sokui'') and the ''[[nengō]]'' was changed to ''[[Shōan]]'' to mark the beginning of a new emperor's reign.<ref>Titsingh, p. 274; Varley, p. 44, 238.</ref>
* '''1299''' (''Einin 7''): The 8th rector of the nunnery at [[Hokkeji]] died.<ref>Meeks, Lori Rachelle. (2010). {{Google books|B4fARMdQkXUC|''Hokkeji and the Reemergence of Female Monastic Orders in Premodern Japan,'' p. 166.|page=166}}</ref> 

