{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}} {{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}} '''Francis Elrington Ball''', known as '''F. Elrington Ball''' (1863–1928), was an Irish author and [[Legal history|legal historian]], best known for his work ''The Judges in Ireland 1221–1921'' (1926).
==Life==
A younger son of [[John Thomas Ball]] (1815 to 1898), the [[Lord Chancellor of Ireland]] from 1875 to 1880, and his wife Catherine Elrington, Ball was unsuccessful in seeking election (as a [[Unionism (Ireland)|Unionist]]) to Parliament at the [[United Kingdom general election, 1900]] in [[South Dublin (UK Parliament constituency)|South Dublin]]. His father had represented [[Dublin University (constituency)|Dublin University]] in Parliament from 1868 to 1875.
[[File:Four Courts Conflagration.jpg|thumb|right|225px|The Four Courts on fire during the Civil War]] Ball is, however, best known for his scholarship, particularly for his work on [[Jonathan Swift|Swift]], the local history of [[Dublin]] and on the history of the judiciary in Ireland from 1221 to 1921. The [[Four Courts#Destruction in Civil War|destruction of the Four Courts]] in 1922, during the [[Irish Civil War]], and of the public records and legal archives it contained (especially those of the [[Irish Public Records Office]]) made Ball's prior research into the history of the Irish judiciary up to 1921 particularly valuable to later scholars. The review published in the ''[[Irish Law Times]] & Solicitors' Journal'' described it as "a truly marvellous condensation of judicial history involving the exhaustive study of a long period, the earlier part of which was hitherto obscure."<ref>{{cite journal |title= Review: ''The Judges in Ireland'' | author = Anon | year = 1927 | journal = I.l.t. & S.j. | volume = lxi | pages = 3–4 }}</ref> The same review characterised Ball as "a writer of great care and accuracy, whose work is always characterised by minute and diligent research."
Ball was also a governor of the [[The King's Hospital|Blue Coat School]], [[Oxmantown]], Dublin.
