'''John of Küküllő''' ({{circa}} 1320{{spaced ndash}}1393) was a Hungarian clergyman, royal official and historian.

== Family ==
Born as John Apród of Tótsolymos, John was the son of Miklós Apród, a nobleman who received Tótsolymos (now [[Šarišské Sokolovce]] in [[Slovakia]]) from [[Charles I of Hungary]].{{sfn|Köblös|1994|p=387}} He was born around 1320.{{sfn|Köblös|1994|p=387}}

== Career ==
He worked as a notary for the royal chancery before 1350.{{sfn|Köblös|1994|p=387}} He became a canon in the [[Arad Chapter]] and the [[Eger Chapter]] in 1352.{{sfn|Köblös|1994|p=387}}

He died between 15 September and 10 December 1393.{{sfn|Köblös|1994|p=387}}

== Chronicle of King Louis ==
He wrote a biography of [[Louis I of Hungary]] after 1360.{{sfn|Köblös|1994|p=387}}{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=158}} He was the first Hungarian historian to use royal charters while writing his book.{{sfn|Köblös|1994|p=387}}

