{{other uses|Legrand (disambiguation)}} {{Infobox person | name = | image = | imagesize = | caption = | birth_name = Philippe Alexandre Ernest Félix Legrand | birth_date = 2 September 1866 | birth_place = [[Saint-Doulchard]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1953|06|01|1866|09|02}} | death_place = [[Culan]] | othername = | occupation = Historian | years_active = | spouse = | signature = }}
'''Philippe-Ernest Legrand''' (2 September 1866<ref name="Mollat">{{Cite news|language=fr|first=Guillaume|last=Mollat|authorlink=Guillaume Mollat|title=Notice sur la vie et les travaux de M. Philippe Legrand|journal=Comptes rendus de l'Académie des inscriptions et belles-lettres|volume=98|issue=4|year=1954|pages=413-418|issn=0065-0536|url=http://www.persee.fr/web/revues/home/prescript/article/crai_0065-0536_1954_num_98_4_10336}}.</ref> – 1 July 1953<ref name="Séchan">{{Cite news|language=fr|first=Louis|last=Séchan|authorlink=Louis Séchan|title=Assemblée générale du 17 juin 1954 – Allocution de M. Louis Séchan|journal=Revue des études grecques|volume=67|issue=316-318|year=1954|pages=19-30|issn=0035-2039|url=http://www.persee.fr/web/revues/home/prescript/article/reg_0035-2039_1954_num_67_316_3367}}. Read « Philippe-Ernest », not Philippe-Emmanuel.</ref>) was a French [[Hellenistic period|Hellenist]]. An historian, philologist, archaeologist, epigrapher, his great work was the translation and editing of [[Histories (Herodotus)]], published in the [[Collection Budé]], which is still a reference.
== Career == Philippe-Ernest Legrand studied at the [[École Normale Supérieure]] from 1885 to 1888<ref name="Mollat"/> and received a doctorate of Letters in 1898; One of his thesis was on Theocritus, and his complementary thesis was entitled ''{{lang|la|Quo animo Graeci praesertim V° et VI° saeculis tum in vita privata tum in publicis rebus divinationem adhibuerint}}''.<ref name="Mollat"/>
He taught at the [[University of Lyon]] from 1891 until 1926. In 1902, he obtained the chair of Greek philology and epigraphy, and then, from 1920, that of Greek language and literature.<ref name="Mollat"/> He took early retirement in 1926, and settled in the [[Château de Culan]] to work on his edition of Herodotus.<ref name="Mollat"/>
He was also a member of the [[French School at Athens]] between 1888 and 1891<ref name="Mollat"/> and a member of the [[Académie des Inscriptions et Belles-Lettres]] from 1933.<ref name="Séchan"/>
== Work == Besides Herodotus, he studied the work of many Greek poets, including the Bucolics. A specialist of literary history, he was also strongly interested in [[Menander]], who was rediscovered at the beginning of the century thanks to the ''[[Oxyrhynchus Papyri]]''<ref name="Séchan"/> as well as in new comedy.<ref name="Séchan"/> An incomplete list of authors on which he worked includes [[Sophron]], [[Callimachus]], [[Herondas]], [[Leonidas of Tarentum]], the pseudo-Theocritus, [[Bion of Phlossa]], [[Moschos]], and [[John Chrysostom]].<ref name="Séchan"/>
