'''Sonchis of Saïs''' or '''the Saïte''' ({{lang-grc-gre|Σῶγχις ὁ Σαΐτης}}, ''Sō̂nkhis o Saḯtēs''; {{fl.|594}} BC) was an [[Ancient Egypt|Egyptian]] [[priest]] who is mentioned in Greek writings as relating the account of [[Atlantis]]. His status as a historical figure is a matter of debate.
The [[Plato]]nic dialogues ''[[Timaeus (dialogue)|Timaeus]]'' and ''[[Critias (dialogue)|Critias]],'' written around 360 BC, relate (through the voice of [[Critias]]) how the Athenian statesman [[Solon]] (638–558 BC) traveled to Egypt and in the city of [[Sais, Egypt|Sais]] encountered the priests of the goddess [[Neith]]. A very aged priest tells him that 9000 years earlier, Athens had been in conflict with the great power of [[Atlantis]], which was then destroyed in a catastrophe.<ref name="Timaeus">Plato, ''[http://classics.mit.edu/Plato/timaeus.html Timaeus]''.</ref>
Plato's dialogue does not mention a name for the priest, but [[Plutarch]] (46–120 AD), in his ''[[Parallel Lives|Life of Solon]]'' identified the aged priest as Sonchis: {{quote|Near Nilus' mouth, by fair [[Canopus, Egypt|Canopus]]' shores, and spent some time in study with Psenophis of [[Heliopolis (ancient Egypt)|Heliopolis]], and Sonchis the Saïte, the most learned of all the priests; from whom, as Plato says, getting knowledge of the Atlantic story, he put it into a poem, and proposed to bring it to the knowledge of the Greeks.<ref name="Solon">Plutarch, ''[http://classics.mit.edu/Plutarch/solon.html Life of Solon]''</ref>}}
Plutarch gives a more detailed description on the Greek philosophers who visited Egypt and received advice by the Egyptian priests in his book ''[[Moralia|On Isis and Osiris]]''. Thus [[Thales of Miletus]], [[Eudoxus of Cnidus]], [[Solon]], [[Pythagoras]], (some say [[Lycurgus of Sparta]] also) and [[Plato]], traveled into Egypt and conversed with the priests. Eudoxus was instructed by Chonupheus of [[Memphis, Egypt|Memphis]], Solon by Sonchis of Saïs and Pythagoras by Oenuphis of Heliopolis.<ref>Plutarch, ''[http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Isis_and_Osiris*/A.html On Isis And Osiris]'', ch. 10.</ref>
