{{primary sources|date=December 2017}}
'''W. Jeffrey Bolster''' is a Professor of history at the [[University of New Hampshire]] in the United States, and the author of ''The Mortal Sea: Fishing the Atlantic in the Age of Sail'',<ref name=wc1>Bolster, W. Jeffrey. The Mortal Sea: Fishing the Atlantic in the Age of Sail. Cambridge, Massachusetts: Belknap Press of Harvard University Press, 2012. {{ISBN|9780674047655}} [http://www.worldcat.org/title/mortal-sea-fishing-the-atlantic-in-the-age-of-sail/oclc/780415768&referer=brief_results WorldCat item record]</ref> which won the 2013 [[Bancroft Prize]] in history of the Americas,<ref>Columbia University Library,2013 Bancroft Winners Announced. [http://library.columbia.edu/news/libraries/2013/2013-3-18_2013_Bancroft_Winners_Announced.html] accessed 27 June 2013</ref> and the 2013 [[Albert J. Beveridge Award]]. He also wrote ''Black Jacks: African American Seamen in the Age of Sail''<ref>Bolster, W. Jeffrey. Black Jacks: African American Seamen in the Age of Sail, published in Cambridge, Massachusetts: Harvard University Press, 1997, {{ISBN|9780674076273}} [http://www.worldcat.org/title/black-jacks-african-american-seamen-in-the-age-of-sail/oclc/35646554&referer=brief_results WorldCat item record]</ref>

==Biography==
Bolster received a BA degree from [[Trinity College (Connecticut)|Trinity College]] in 1976, a MA from [[Brown University]] in 1984 , and a PhD from Johns Hopkins University in 1992.<ref>[https://cola.unh.edu/faculty-member/jeffrey-bolster Official Web Page at  University of New Hampshire]</ref>

