'''William Abel Pantin''' [[Fellow of the British Academy|FBA]] (1 May 1902 – 10 November 1973) was an historian of [[England in the Middle Ages|mediaeval England]] who spent most of his academic life at the [[University of Oxford]].

==Life==
Pantin was born in [[Blackheath, London|Blackheath]], south London, on 1 May 1902. He was educated at [[Westminster School]] and [[Christ Church, Oxford]], where he obtained a first-class degree in Modern History in 1923.<ref name=HighfieldIV>{{harvnb|Highfield|1974|p=iv}}</ref> He undertook research at the [[University of Oxford]] after winning a Bryce Research Studentship.<ref name=HighfieldIV/>

From 1926 he taught history at the [[Victoria University of Manchester]], first as an Assistant Lecturer and then as the [[James Fraser (bishop)|Bishop Fraser]] Lecturer. At Manchester he worked under [[F. M. Powicke]], Professor of Mediaeval History, who influenced Pantin's work for the rest of his life.<ref name=HighfieldIV/> In 1929 the [[Royal Historical Society]] awarded its Alexander Prize to Pantin for his essay ''The General and Provincial Chapters of the English Black Monks, 1215–1540''.<ref name=HighfieldIV/> The "Black Monks" were the [[Order of Saint Benedict]], whose history in England remained a subject of Pantin's research and published works for the rest of his life.<ref name=HighfieldIV/>

In 1928 Powicke moved to Oxford to become [[Regius Professor of Modern History (Oxford)|Regius Professor of Modern History]].<ref name=HighfieldIV/> In 1933 Pantin followed, becoming a tutorial [[Oxbridge Fellow|fellow]] and Lecturer in History at [[Oriel College, Oxford]].<ref name=HighfieldIV/> He was also a university lecturer in mediaeval archaeology and history from 1937 onwards.{{citation needed|date=October 2013}}

Pantin was active in the [[Oxfordshire Architectural and Historical Society|Oxford Architectural and Historical Society]] (OAHS), serving on the Editorial Committee of its journal ''Oxoniensia'' and on the OAHS's Sub-Committee for Old Houses.<ref name=HighfieldV>{{harvnb|Highfield|1974|p=v}}</ref> He was President of the OAHS 1959–64.<ref name=HighfieldV/>

During his career at Oxford a substantial number of the city's unique mediaeval buildings were destroyed for redevelopment. In 1936–37 the University of Oxford had a row of historic houses in [[Broad Street, Oxford|Broad Street]] demolished to make way for the [[New Bodleian Library]].<ref name=Pantin1937>{{cite journal |last=Pantin |first=W.A. |year=1937 |title=The Recently Demolished Houses in Broad Street |journal=[[Oxoniensia]] |volume=II |pages=171–200 |publisher=[[Oxfordshire Architectural and Historical Society|Oxford Architectural and Historical Society]] |url= http://oxoniensia.org/volumes/1937/pantin.pdf}}</ref> In 1954–55 [[F. W. Woolworth Company|F. W. Woolworth]] had the mediaeval Clarendon Hotel in [[Cornmarket Street]] demolished to make way for a new retail store.<ref name=Pantin1958>{{cite journal |last=Pantin |first=W.A. |year=1958 |title=The Clarendon Hotel Oxford. Part II: The Buildings |journal=[[Oxoniensia]] |volume=XXIII |pages=84–129 |publisher=[[Oxfordshire Architectural and Historical Society|Oxford Architectural and Historical Society]] |url= http://oxoniensia.org/volumes/1958/pantin.pdf}}</ref> In 1959 [[Oxford City Council]] had Lower Fisher Row beside [[Castle Mill Stream]] demolished as [[slum clearance]].<ref name=Pantin1960>{{cite journal |last=Pantin |first=W.A. |year=1960 |title=Houses of the Oxford Region. I. Fisher Row, Oxford |journal=[[Oxoniensia]] |volume=XXV |location=Oxford |publisher=[[Oxfordshire Architectural and Historical Society|Oxford Architectural and Historical Society]] |pages=121–125 |url= http://oxoniensia.org/volumes/1960/pantin.pdf}}</ref> In each case Pantin recorded the buildings as fully as possible before and during their demolition, and published his results in ''Oxoniensia''.<ref name=Pantin1937/><ref name=Pantin1958/><ref name=Pantin1960/>

In 1940 Pantin was appointed General Editor of the [[Oxford Historical Society]].<ref name=HighfieldV/> He developed an interest in the archives of the University of Oxford, which in 1946 appointed him [[Keeper of the Archives]].<ref name=HighfieldV/>

Pantin was appointed a [[Fellow of the British Academy]] (FBA) in 1948 and was a member of the [[Royal Commission on the Historical Monuments of England]] from 1963 onwards.<ref name=Who>{{harvnb|Who Was Who 1920–2008|December 2007|p=}}{{page needed|date=October 2013}}</ref>

Pantin retired from his college and university posts in 1969, and Oriel College made him an Honorary Fellow in 1971.<ref name=Who/> He died on 10 November 1973.<ref name=HighfieldV/>

==Charitable trust==
There was a William Abel Pantin Trust to further historical research in Oxford and support the charitable and educational functions of the Provost and Fellows of Oriel College, Oxford.<ref name=CC>{{cite web |url= http://apps.charitycommission.gov.uk/Showcharity/RegisterOfCharities/RemovedCharityMain.aspx?RegisteredCharityNumber=309718&SubsidiaryNumber=0 |title=William Abel Pantin Trust (ICW Oriel College Oxford) |publisher=[[Charity Commission for England and Wales]] |accessdate=17 October 2013}}</ref> It was founded in January 1971 and dissolved in August 2013.<ref name=CC/>

